<title>Pentatonic Scale</title>
<h2> PENTATONIC SCALE </h2> <br>

<li class="list-group-item">
<p>A pentatonic scale is like any other scale (notes separated by intervals), but it contains just 5 tones, hence the Greek word "pentatonic", which simply means five. Recall that most scales in western music contain 7 notes (e.g. the major scale, minor scale, etc), which makes the pentatonic a smaller scale.
<br><br>
The pentatonic scale has 2 variations - major and minor. These are used very very often in jazz, blues and rock (blues is the basis of rock), and across other genres as well.
<br><br>
The pentatonic scales are a “economy” version of the bigger major and minor scales, as it is cut down to 5 notes. The omitted notes have a definite effect on the overall mood of the music you’ll make.</p> <br>


